## A $6 billion market growing at 15%, but restaurant spending is stubbornly low

The global restaurant management software market sits at **$5.5–6.7 billion (2024/2025)** and is growing at **13–17% CAGR**, projected to reach $14–28 billion by 2030–2034, depending on definition breadth. The analytics and business intelligence segment is the fastest-growing sub-category at **~17.25% CAGR**, projected from $1.42 billion (2025) to $3.68 billion (2031). The online reputation management market overall is **$5–7 billion**, with hospitality accounting for roughly **10–15%** of that — placing the restaurant/hospitality ORM market at approximately **$500 million to $1 billion** globally.

The European restaurant management software market represents roughly **$1.4–1.7 billion** of the global total. The DACH region contains approximately **255,000–285,000 restaurant establishments** — Germany with ~165,000–175,000, Switzerland with ~50,849, and Austria with an estimated 40,000–60,000. Switzerland's foodservice market alone was **CHF 20.9 billion** in 2023, with GDP per capita of ~$104,000 making it one of the world's wealthiest dining markets. Higher average check sizes mean each percentage point of improvement carries more absolute revenue impact than in most other markets.

Here's the bearish reality on spending, though: **restaurants spend only 1–2% of revenue on technology**, and for small independents (under $500K revenue), actual software spending is closer to **0.4% of revenue** — essentially just their POS system. The median reputation management buyer budgets **~$88/user/month** according to Capterra. While 78% of restaurant IT budgets are planned to increase and 28% of operators plan to invest in AI, there's a massive gap between intent and action. Among ~85 chains actively using AI, **only 9% report "meaningful impact"** so far, and 37% cite fragmented systems and data as preventing ROI. The restaurant industry's **~4% pre-tax profit margins** and **80% annual staff turnover** mean operators are perpetually in survival mode, not innovation mode.

