## AI agent capabilities have leapt forward in Q1 2026

The technology infrastructure for this business is dramatically better than it was six months ago, driven by three converging developments.

**Model capabilities have crossed critical thresholds.** Claude Opus 4.6 (released February 5, 2026) offers a **14.5-hour autonomous task completion horizon** — the longest of any AI model — with 1M-token context windows at $5/$25 per million tokens (a 67% price cut from its predecessor). Claude's Computer Use Agent launched March 23, 2026 as a research preview, enabling AI to control desktop applications directly. Claude Managed Agents entered public beta April 1, offering fully managed cloud environments where AI can read files, browse the web, and execute code autonomously. OpenAI's GPT-5 series introduced GPT-5-nano at **$0.05/$0.40 per million tokens**, making always-on monitoring agents economically viable — a customer support chatbot processing 10,000 conversations/month now costs roughly **$2–10/month** in API fees.

**The infrastructure layer has standardized.** Anthropic's Model Context Protocol (MCP), originally launched in late 2024, has become the **de facto industry standard** for connecting LLMs to external tools, with over 10,000 active public MCP servers and 97M+ monthly SDK downloads. OpenAI's Responses API now supports remote MCP servers natively. Google's Agent Development Kit supports MCP. This means integrations built for one AI provider work across all of them — dramatically reducing the engineering burden for a vertical AI business.

**Multi-agent orchestration has matured for production use.** Frameworks like LangGraph, CrewAI, and OpenAI's Agents SDK enable production-grade multi-agent systems with built-in governance, tracing, and error handling. A restaurant operations system could deploy specialized agents for review monitoring, complaint escalation, reservation optimization, and report generation — each using the cheapest appropriate model tier (nano for monitoring, mid-tier for analysis, premium for complex recommendations). The practical cost for a moderately complex restaurant operations agent: **$50–200/month per location**.

The Menlo Ventures analysis from April 7, 2026 captures the strategic shift precisely: "Vertical SaaS showed and assisted; **vertical AI reasons and executes**. This moves the ROI calculation from software budgets to people budgets." The implication for restaurants: AI consulting isn't competing for the ~$88/month software budget — it's competing for the **$1,500–$15,000/month consulting retainer** or the **$58,000/year** equivalent of a junior operations analyst.

