## Pricing must bridge the SaaS-consulting gap

Current market pricing establishes clear benchmarks across the value chain:

| Category | Price Range | Notes |
|---|---|---|
| Review management SaaS | $39/year (re:spondelligent entry) to $449/month (Birdeye Professional) | Per-location pricing standard |
| Restaurant analytics platforms | $59–$600/month | Lightspeed ($59–$239), Restaurant365 ($400–$600+) |
| AI-specific restaurant tools | $79–$225/month per location | Lineup.ai ($79–$149), Bloom Intelligence ($205–$225) |
| Restaurant consulting (hourly) | $75–$300/hour | New consultants: $75–$150; experienced: $150–$300 |
| Restaurant consulting (monthly retainer) | $1,500–$15,000/month | Basic advisory: $1,500–$5,000; fractional executive: $5,000–$15,000 |
| Restaurant consulting (project) | $2,000–$50,000+ | Menu overhaul: $3,000–$10,000; full operational audit: $10,000–$25,000 |

The opportunity lies in the **gap between SaaS pricing ($100–$300/month) and consulting pricing ($1,500–$15,000/month)**. A hybrid model — say, CHF 500–1,500/month per location combining AI-powered monitoring, quarterly financial impact reports, and a defined set of automation implementations — occupies pricing whitespace. This is significantly cheaper than a retainer consultant yet delivers far more operational value than a self-service dashboard. For Swiss restaurant groups with 5–35 locations and average check sizes of CHF 40–80+, a demonstrable 2–5% revenue improvement from better review management and operational optimization justifies this spend multiple times over. Restaurants working with consultants report an **average 12–15% increase in profitability** — the key is proving that an AI-augmented consulting model delivers comparable results at lower cost.

